      <hedline>
        <hl1>What to Look For as Bush and Gore Debate</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Greg Grandin letter comments on Richard Goodwin's Sept 30 Op-Ed on presidential debates</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Debate Tips From J.F.K.,'' by Richard N. Goodwin (Op-Ed, Sept. 30):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Debate Tips From J.F.K.,'' by Richard N. Goodwin (Op-Ed, Sept. 30):</p>
        <p>At a time of steadily diminishing political expectations, Mr. Goodwin feels that it is necessary to remind the two presidential candidates that when it comes to debates, it is style (music) rather than substance (words) that wins voters. Perhaps a dissonant note, in the form of a third debater, is what is needed to get the voters to listen to the lyrics.</p>
        <p>GREG GRANDIN  Durham, N.C., Sept. 30, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an assistant professor of history at Duke University.</p>
      </block>
